In its war with Iran, Riyadh has its sights set on Lebanon’s most powerful political force.
Saudi Arabia said its air defenses had taken down a rocket aimed at residential areas, while the rebels said they had been targeting a royal palace.
With last weekend’s arrests of princes and business tycoons, the country’s carefully constructed balance may be at risk.
King Salman’s trip, the first state visit by a Saudi monarch, is a sign of the shifting dynamics in the Middle East as Russia assumes a greater role.
The kingdom released Prince Mutaib bin Abdullah, the former head of the National Guard, a sign it is moving to resolve corruption charges.
The kingdom’s crown prince seems to think that modernization requires an absolute monarch.
Competition between the two regimes to earn the mantle of the more moderate Islamic alternative benefits feminists.
If Mohammed bin Salman is serious about moderate Islam, he should allow debate on foundational Islamic texts.

The arrest of Prince Alwaleed bin Talal, the country’s most prominent investor, has caused unease among Western businessmen wary of the lack of transparency.

Justices dismissed two petitions to overturn the victory last month by Uhuru Kenyatta, a decision that came after a weekend of unrest.
Kenya’s protracted presidential election badly hit the economy, affecting people across the social spectrum.
The country went to the polls on Thursday, but scuffles broke out and the police fired tear gas at protesters in an area of Nairobi.
Many in the country are asking themselves how, after the national trauma of post-vote violence 10 years ago, they have ended up with a crisis yet again.
The opposition politician Raila Odinga returned from abroad, and his supporters fought with the police.
Kenya needs a transparent, credible and peaceful re-election. The world will be watching.
Mr. Kenyatta also won a vote in August that was nullified by the Supreme Court, but the new balloting was met by confusion and mistrust.
The army marched into the town of Lasu in the country’s southwest, capturing a rebel headquarters.
With so little participation, some fear that millions of Kenyans won’t accept the results.
